Bioinformatic Analysis Pipeline
Version: Reproducible analysis for microbiome study
Paper Title: Bilophila wadsworthia inhibits lifestyle intervention response in Gestational Diabetes Mellitus via L-glutamine regulation
1. Sequencing Data
Raw sequencing data were submitted to the NCBI SRA database under the accession number: PRJNA898150.

2. Analysis Platform
Data analysis was performed using the Majorbio Cloud (www.majorbio.com).
Reference: Zhao, Jianhua.et al. 2026. Majorbio Cloud 2026 Provides Comprehensive Analysis Workflows for Microbiome. iMeta e70109. doi:10.1002/imt2.70109.

3. Data Quality Control
3.1. Adapter trimming was performed at both 5' and 3' ends using fastp[1] v0.20.0 (https://github.com/OpenGene/fastp).
3.2. Reads with length < 50 bp, average base quality < 20, or containing ambiguous N bases were removed. High-quality paired-end and single-end reads were retained.
3.3. Reads were aligned to the host DNA sequence using BWA[2] v0.7.9a (http://bio-bwa.sourceforge.net/), and highly similar host-contaminated reads were removed.

4. De Novo Assembly
Clean reads were assembled using MEGAHIT[3] v1.1.2 (https://github.com/voutcn/megahit).
Contigs ≥ 300 bp were retained for subsequent analysis.

5. Gene Prediction
Open reading frames (ORFs) were predicted from assembled contigs using MetaGene[4] (http://metagene.cb.k.u-tokyo.ac.jp/).
Only genes with nucleotide length ≥ 100 bp were kept and translated into amino acid sequences.

6. Non-Redundant Gene Catalog Construction
All predicted genes were clustered using CD-HIT[5] v4.6.1 (http://www.bioinformatics.org/cd-hit/) with parameters:
- 90% identity
- 90% coverage
The longest sequence in each cluster was selected as the representative to construct a non-redundant gene set.

7. Gene Abundance Calculation
High-quality reads of each sample were mapped to the non-redundant gene set using SOAPaligner[6] v2.21 (http://soap.genomics.org.cn/) with 95% identity.
Gene abundance in each sample was calculated based on mapped reads.


8. Taxonomic and Functional Annotation

8.1 Taxonomic Annotation (NR Database)
Amino acid sequences were aligned against the NR database using Diamond[7] v0.8.35 (http://diamondsearch.org/index.php) with BLASTP E-value ≤ 1e-5.
Taxonomic annotations were assigned based on NR taxonomy, and species abundance was calculated as the total abundance of corresponding genes.

8.2 KEGG Functional Annotation
Amino acid sequences were aligned against the KEGG database using Diamond v0.8.35 with E-value ≤ 1e-5.
KO and Pathway abundance was calculated as the total abundance of corresponding genes.

9. Diversity Analysis

9.1 Alpha Diversity
Alpha diversity indices (Sob, Ace, Chao) at the genus level were calculated in R v3.3.1.
Differences between GDM-R-0w and GDM-NR-0w were tested using Wilcoxon rank-sum test (two-tailed), with FDR adjustment for multiple comparisons.

9.2 Beta Diversity
Beta diversity distance matrices were calculated using QIIME 2 2020.2.0. NMDS ordination and plotting were performed in R v3.3.1 with the vegan v2.4.3 package.

Beta diversity analysis pipeline:
A. Community dissimilarity was quantified using the Bray–Curtis distance.
B. Community structure was visualized using NMDS.
C. Betadisper was used to test homogeneity of group dispersions.
D. ANOSIM was used to test the significance of between-group differences.

10. Differential Abundance Analysis

10.1 Species & Function Differences
Abundances were calculated using read counts.
Wilcoxon rank-sum test (two-tailed) was applied, with FDR adjustment and 95% confidence intervals estimated by Bootstrap.

10.2 LEfSe Analysis
LEfSe analysis was performed at http://galaxy.biobakery.org/.
- Wilcoxon rank-sum test was used to detect differentially abundant species.
- Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) was used to estimate effect size.
- Threshold: LDA score > 3.0 at the species level.

10.3 Correlation Heatmap and Mantel Test Network Analysis 
Analyses were performed in R v4.1.1 using the linket and vegan packages.
- Correlation tests: Pearson correlation
- Mantel test: Spearman method, with 999 permutations  
Significance and visualization rules: 
- p < 0.05: black lines
- p < 0.01: orange lines
Line thickness was scaled by Mantel correlation coefficient r.  

10.4 Volcano Plot Analysis of Differential Non-Targeted Metabolites 
Volcano plots were constructed in R v4.1.1 using the ggplot2 and ggrepel packages. 
Thresholds:
- |logFC| ≥ 0.5
- p < 0.05
Upregulated metabolites were colored blue, downregulated metabolites red.
The geom_text_repel function was used to avoid label overlapping.   

